      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 14px;">What Happens After an Arrest in Washington County?</h2>
      <div style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.75;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">When someone is arrested in Washington County, they are transported to the Washington County Correctional Facility at 611 SW Adams Boulevard in Bartlesville for booking. The facility, managed under Sheriff Scott Owen, has a capacity of approximately 60 inmates and is staffed by over 74 corrections officers and support personnel. The booking process includes identity verification, a health assessment, inventory of personal belongings, fingerprinting, and a booking photograph. Charges are entered into the system, warrant status is reviewed, and bail is set according to the court's bond schedule.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Once bail is set, a family member or friend can contact Angel Bail Bonds at (405) 614-3000 to begin the release process. We verify the inmate's information and bail amount directly with the Washington County Correctional Facility at (918) 332-4011. After paperwork is completed — which can be done entirely by phone or e-sign — we post bail at the facility. The jail then begins release processing, which typically takes 1-2 hours. Distance from Stillwater to Bartlesville is approximately 95 miles or 1 hour 47 minutes via US-177 N and US-75 N, which many families appreciate when managing detention facility logistics remotely.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Washington County accepts cash, money orders, and credit cards for direct cash bail payments. However, most families choose to work with a bail bondsman because posting the full cash bail amount is significantly more expensive. With Angel Bail Bonds, you pay a competitive premium — typically 10% of the bail amount — rather than the full cash bail, and we handle all the logistics with the jail and court. We accept Zelle and Venmo in addition to Visa, Mastercard, and cash, making the bail process flexible and accessible.</p>
