        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Washington County is located in northeastern Oklahoma, approximately 95 miles and 1 hour 47 minutes north of Stillwater. The county seat is Bartlesville, a city of approximately 40,000 people known as the home of Phillips Petroleum (now ConocoPhillips) headquarters. The county has a total population of approximately 52,455 residents spread across picturesque communities in the rolling hills of northeastern Oklahoma.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Bartlesville is a major commercial and cultural hub featuring the iconic Price Tower, designed by renowned architect Frank Lloyd Wright, and the Woolaroc Museum, a world-class art and wildlife facility. The city sits at the intersection of US-60 and US-75, providing accessibility from throughout the region. Law enforcement activity in Washington County includes traffic stops along US-75 and US-60, commercial district incidents in downtown Bartlesville, and arrests at the various state and local establishments that serve the county's substantial daytime population.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 14px;">Other communities in Washington County include Dewey, Copan, Ochelata, Ramona, Vera, Wann, and Lenapah — all charming rural towns with historical significance to northeastern Oklahoma. The county's economy is historically tied to petroleum and energy production, though it has diversified in recent decades. Angel Bail Bonds has served Washington County families for over 15 years and maintains strong working relationships with the Washington County Sheriff's Office under Sheriff Scott Owen and the court system under Court Clerk Jean Davis.</p>
